The performance of the PEC biosensor for the detection of miRNA-159b and miRNA-166a was subsequently investigated under the optimal experiment conditions. As shown in Fig. 3
                        A, the PEC response increased with miRNA-159b concentration from 0.5 fM to 5 pM, with a linear relationship (R = 0.9934) established between the photocurrent and the logarithm of miRNA-159b concentration (Fig. 3B). The linear regression equation was I (nA) = 10.36 logc (fM) + 29.77, with the detection limit was estimated to be around 0.15 fM (S/N = 3). At a constant miRNA-159b concentration (5 pM), the PEC response decreased on increasing the concentration of miRNA-166a from 0.5 fM to 5 pM (Fig. 3C). Fig. 3D confirmed a linear relationship between the photocurrent and logarithm of the miRNA-166a concentration, as described by the equation I (nA) = −9.34 logc (fM) + 61.53 (R = 0.9942). The miRNA-166a detection limit was 0.21 fM. Compared with the previous strategies for miRNA detection (Table 1
                        ), this PEC biosensor developed herein exhibited a low detection limit with a wider linear range, indicating its performance superiority.
